This report explores a dataset containing white wine quality and attributes for almost 4,900 wines.

This dataset contains 13 variabes and 4898 observations.

From this graph it is clear that majority of wines fall into 5, 6, and 7 rating. Notice that quality is always a whole number.

This praph shows us distribution of citric acid which add ’freshness" and flavor to wines. It looks like most of them below 0.5 level. There is a spike at the level around 0.48 which seems to be a common level of citric acid.

First, we can see that this is a long tail data with a couple of outliers. After taking a closer look it is noticable that there are a few wines below residual sugar level of 1 which is quite rare.

Univariate Analysis

There are 4898 white wines with 13 feature(Fixed acidity, volatile acidity, citric acid, residual sugar, chlorides, free sulfur dioxode, total sulfur dioxide, density, pH, sulphates, alcohol, and quality). All of them are numeric values and quality measured only in a whole number.

Other observations: * Most of the wines have a quality of 5, 6, or 7. * Other attributes explored so far have quite normal distribution.

The main feature of this data set is quality. I’d like to determine which attributes have the biggest effect on the quality.

I think volatile acidity, citric acid, chlorides, total sulfur dioxide likely to contribute to the quality of wine because they directly effect the taste or smell of the wine.

I have not created new variables so far.

I log transformed some of the data to have a better understanding of the distribution. What I have notcied it is that most of wines have low residual sugar level which determines the sweetness of the wine.

Density correlates with alcohol and sugar content which makes sense as the density of water is close to that of water depending on the percent of alcohol and sugar content.

Free sulfur dioxide correlates with total sulfur dioxide which also make sense as free sulfur dioxide is a fraction of total amount.

The strongest correlation quality has with density, alcohol, chlorides, and volatile acidity which makes sense because they directly affect the taste of the wine. Let’s take a closer look at scatter plots involving quality and listed above attributes.

After deaper exploration it looks like correlation between quality and density isn’t very strong.

With correlation line, it looks like higher quality wines tend to higher alcohol level.

Although the correlation isn’t very strong it is negative which makes sense since chlorides is the amount of salt in the wine which might affect the taste.

Volatile acidity is a very similar case to chlorides above as too high levels can lead to an unpleasant, vinegar taste.

Now, I want to take a closer look at the alcohol level for different quality levels.

It looks interesting since it is not a linear correlation because wines with quality 5 have the lowest level of alcohol.

It is an obvious correlation between them which is expected.

Fixed acidity and volatile acidity are both very centralized at lower levels.

Wines with higher alcohol tend to have less sugar amount.

Bivariate Analysis

After plotting some box plots and scatter plots I found out how attributes correlate with quality. Majority of them affect how it was assumes based on the correlation data I got at the beginning, however, I found interesting trend about alcohol level which I would like to explore more as it is one of the strongest relations.

Then I looked into some relation between the attributes of the quality of the wine. Majority of them performed as expected. Interesting that wines with higher alcohol level have less sugar.

Multivariate Plots Section

With small variation wines of all qualities have the same trend of having less sugar and less alcohol. However, it looks like there is more high-quality wines with higher alcohol level which you can see from the plot before. The first graph uses mean residual sugar. Also, I grouped wines quality into 3 groups: low, average, and high-quality wines. This will allow for cleaner visualization.

There is a negative correlation between density and alcohol for wines of different quality.

Correlation between pH and fixed acidity is also confirmed for all wine qualities.

Once again it seems like there is the same trend for all quality of wines.

Multivariate Analysis

Multivariate Analysis supports and confirms many findings from Bivariate Analysis section. Additionally, it allowed seeing the differences between the different qualities of wines. Although it looks like the different quality of wines follows the same trend sometime it might slightly vary.

Some interesting findings include higher alcohol level with lower density level and lower residual sugar level for higher alcohol levels which is interesting.

Final Plots and Summary

Plot One

Description One

This is a basic graph which helps to understand us the distribution of wines by quality. There are not that many wines at higher or lower levels. Most of them are in the middle which is an important factor to account when doing the analysis.

Plot Two

Description Two

I find this box plot very interesting because it shows that low-quality wines have higher alcohol level than average ones. This proves that quality and alcohol is not a linear correlation.

Plot Three

Description Three

This graph is also very interesting as it shows that it is very likely for high-quality wine to have low residual sugar level and at the same time have high alcohol level when for average quality wines it doesn’t quite work the same way. Even if the wine contains less sugar it still can be of lower quality or have lower alcohol level.

Reflection

The main purpose and goal of my analysis was to find any significant differences between high and low-quality wine. This data set of different white wines was limited as the majority of wines fall into average quality. It was difficult for me to track a small change which would affect the quality of the wine. Although I was able to find some attributes such as residual sugar, density, chlorides which do affect the quality the effect seems to be very similar.

I think this data would be more interesting to explore if it would include a description oh how actually score was generated as well as to include the price of each wine.
